AbortController — interview talking points

Why I'm using it: handles two issues with async work in useEffect — StrictMode double-invoke (duplicate fetches in dev) and component unmount mid-fetch (wasted requests + setState on unmounted component).
How it works: new AbortController() in effect, pass signal to fetch, cleanup calls controller.abort(). Fetch rejects with AbortError, catch returns early — no setState.
Why not isMounted ref: only drops the response, doesn't cancel the actual request. Also React 18 removed the unmount warning, so the pattern is outdated.
Gotcha: controller is single-use, need a fresh one per request. Inner try/catch should re-throw AbortError so outer handler sees it.


```js
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  const fetchData = async () => {
    try {
      const res = await fetch('/api/jobs', { signal: controller.signal });
      const data = await res.json();
      setJobs(data);
    } catch (err) {
      if (err.name === 'AbortError') return;
      console.error(err);
    }
  };

  fetchData();

  return () => controller.abort();
}, []);
```

Stale closure：setJobIds(ids) 后同一函数里读 jobIds 还是旧的 → 用本地变量 let ids = jobIds
时间戳错误：new Date().toLocaleDateString(job.time) 三处错 → new Date(job.time * 1000).toLocaleDateString()
Promise.allSettled + 内层 try/catch 混用：返回结构变了 forEach 解构会崩
StrictMode 用 didMount ref 不管用：cleanup 里重置 flag 会被下一次 setup 立刻撤销 → 用 one-way latch（只 false→true 不重置）或 AbortController

如何给promise 嵌套id
const promises = ids.map(id =>
  fetch(url(id))
    .then(r => {
      if (!r.ok) throw Object.assign(new Error(`HTTP ${r.status}`), { id });
      return r.json();
    })
    .then(data => ({ id, data }))   // ← 成功也要手动塞 id
);
